[{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Optimal-Synthesis-Construction","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"","title":"Optimal Synthesis Construction"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Introduction","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"The construction of optimal synthesis for production-regeneration systems is a crucial step that allows determining the complete structure of optimal solutions depending on initial and final conditions. This approach provides a global understanding of the system behavior and enables rapid calculation of optimal solutions without having to solve complex optimization problems each time.","title":"Introduction"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Synthesis-Theory","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"","title":"Synthesis Theory"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Fundamental-Principle","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"Optimal synthesis is based on Pontryagin's maximum principle and switching arc analysis. For our production-regeneration system, we characterize all possible types of arcs:\n\nProduction arc sigma_+ : u = +1\nRegeneration arc sigma_- : u = -1  \nSingular arc sigma_s : u = u_s with dot x = 0","title":"Fundamental Principle"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Hamiltonian-Function","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"The system Hamiltonian is written as:\n\nH(x p u) = frac1 + u2 (l_p(x) + p cdot f_p(x) + q cdot g_p(x)) + frac1 - u2 (l_r(x) + p cdot f_r(x) + q cdot g_r(x))\n\nwhere p and q are the adjoint variables associated with states x and y.","title":"Hamiltonian Function"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Optimality-Conditions","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"The optimal control is given by:\n\nu^*(x p) = begincases\n+1  textif  H(x p +1)  H(x p -1) \n-1  textif  H(x p +1)  H(x p -1) \nu_s  textif  H(x p +1) = H(x p -1)\nendcases","title":"Optimality Conditions"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Practical-Construction","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"","title":"Practical Construction"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Step-1:-Switching-Point-Analysis","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"Switching points between different arc types are determined by the equality of Hamiltonians:\n\nH(x p +1) = H(x p -1)\n\nThis condition defines a switching surface in the phase space (x p).","title":"Step 1: Switching Point Analysis"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Step-2:-Singular-Arc-Calculation","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"Singular arcs satisfy:\n\nfracddt fracpartial Hpartial u = 0\n\nFor our system, this leads to the condition dot x = 0, which means the fouling state remains constant during the singular arc.","title":"Step 2: Singular Arc Calculation"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Step-3:-Structure-Assembly","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"The possible optimal structures are:\n\nPure production : sigma_+\nRegeneration followed by production : sigma_- sigma_+\nSingular arc followed by production : sigma_s sigma_+\nRegeneration, singular arc, production : sigma_- sigma_s sigma_+\nProduction, singular arc, production : sigma_+ sigma_s sigma_+","title":"Step 3: Structure Assembly"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Construction-Algorithm","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"using CTMembraneFiltration\nusing Plots\n\n# System parameters\nparams = (\n    lp = x -> x^2,           # production cost\n    lr = x -> 0.5*x,         # regeneration cost  \n    fp = x -> -0.1*x,        # production dynamics\n    fr = x -> 0.2*(1-x),     # regeneration dynamics\n    gp = x -> 1.0,           # production\n    gr = x -> 0.0            # no production during regeneration\n)\n\n# Construct synthesis\nsynthesis = construct_optimal_synthesis(params)\n\n# Visualize control regions\nplot_control_regions(synthesis)","title":"Construction Algorithm"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Region-Determination","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"# Compute optimal control regions\nregions = compute_control_regions(synthesis)\n\n# Display boundaries\nplot_switching_curves(regions)","title":"Region Determination"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Optimal-Trajectory-Calculation","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"# Initial and final points\nx0 = 1.5\ny0 = 0.0\nT = 10.0\n\n# Compute optimal trajectory\noptimal_trajectory = compute_optimal_trajectory(x0, y0, T, synthesis)\n\n# Visualization\nplot(optimal_trajectory.time, optimal_trajectory.state, \n     label=\"Optimal trajectory\", xlabel=\"Time\", ylabel=\"State\")","title":"Optimal Trajectory Calculation"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Practical-Applications","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"","title":"Practical Applications"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Case-1:-Low-Initial-Fouling","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"For x_0  x_s (where x_s is the singular state), the optimal structure is typically sigma_+ (pure production).","title":"Case 1: Low Initial Fouling"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Case-2:-Moderate-Fouling","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"For x_s  x_0  x_c (where x_c is the switching point), the optimal structure is sigma_- sigma_+.","title":"Case 2: Moderate Fouling"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Case-3:-High-Fouling","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"For x_0  x_c, the optimal structure may include a singular arc: sigma_- sigma_s sigma_+.","title":"Case 3: High Fouling"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Numerical-Validation","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"# Validate synthesis against direct resolution\ntest_points = [(x0=0.5, T=5.0), (x0=1.0, T=8.0), (x0=1.5, T=10.0)]\n\nfor (i, point) in enumerate(test_points)\n    # Solution by synthesis\n    sol_synthesis = solve_by_synthesis(point.x0, 0.0, point.T, synthesis)\n    \n    # Direct solution\n    sol_direct = solve_direct(point.x0, 0.0, point.T)\n    \n    # Comparison\n    error = compute_error(sol_synthesis, sol_direct)\n    println(\"Point $i: error = $error\")\nend","title":"Numerical Validation"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Advantages-of-Synthesis-Approach","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"Computational speed: Once synthesis is constructed, solutions are obtained instantly\nGlobal understanding: Provides an overview of all possible solutions\nRobustness: Less sensitive to numerical errors than direct methods\nParametric analysis: Easy to study as a function of system parameters","title":"Advantages of Synthesis Approach"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Limitations-and-Extensions","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"","title":"Limitations and Extensions"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Current-Limitations","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"Regularity assumptions on dynamics\nSimple quadratic costs\nAbsence of additional state constraints","title":"Current Limitations"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#Possible-Extensions","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"Inclusion of state constraints x(t) leq x_max\nMore general costs (non-convex)\nSystems with multiple operating modes\nParameter uncertainties","title":"Possible Extensions"},{"category":"section","location":"optimal_synthesis.html#References","page":"Optimal synthesis","text":"Dutto, R., Cots, O., & Martinon, P. (2026). Optimal control of production-regeneration systems with application to membrane filtration. HAL-05493075.\nBryson, A. E., & Ho, Y. C. (1975). Applied optimal control. Taylor & Francis.\nPontryagin, L. S., et al. (1962). The mathematical theory of optimal processes. Interscience Publishers.","title":"References"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Introduction","page":"Introduction","text":"Production–regeneration systems describe processes that must alternate between a productive phase and a recovery phase. During production, the system generates an output (for example filtered water), but this phase also progressively degrades an internal state (such as fouling or resistance). The regeneration phase does the opposite: it restores the system’s internal condition, but does not directly produce useful output.\n\n    <img src=\"./assets/backwash.jpg\" width=\"800px\">\n\nSuch a system can naturally be formulated as an optimal control problem. The main objective of this package is to provide tools to analyze and solve problems of this type.","title":"Introduction"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Problem-statement","page":"Introduction","text":"We consider the following three-dimensional dynamical system defined for both production and regeneration modes: \n\nu = +1  left beginarrayrl\ndot c(t) = l_p(x(t)) 05em\ndot x(t) = f_p(x(t)) 05em\ndot y(t) = g_p(x(t))\nendarray right\nquad textand quad  \nu = -1  left beginarrayrl\ndot c(t) = l_r(x(t)) 05em\ndot x(t) = f_r(x(t)) 05em\ndot y(t) = g_r(x(t))\nendarray right\n\nwhere :\n\nc denotes the cost,\nx represents the internal state of the system,\ny is an auxiliary state associated with a target value (or budget constraint), denoted by T.\n\nLet u in -1 1 be the control variable, where u = +1 denotes production mode and u = -1 denotes regeneration mode, we consider the following optimal control problem\n\ntext(OCP) quad\nleft \nbegin arrayll\ndisplaystyle min_xyt_f int_t_0^t_f frac1 + u(t)2 l_p(x(t)) + frac1-u(t)2 l_r(x(t))  mathrm dt \n t in t_0 t_f  mathrmae 1em\ndisplaystyle mathrmst  dot x(t) = frac1 + u(t)2 f_p(x(t)) + frac1-u(t)2 f_r(x(t))  t in t_0 t_f  mathrmae 1em \ndisplaystyle phantommathrmst   dot y(t) = frac1 + u(t)2 g_p(x(t)) + frac1-u(t)2 g_r(x(t))   t in t_0 t_f  mathrmae 1em\nphantommathrmst   u(t) in -1 1  t in t_0 t_f 1em\nphantommathrmst   x(t_0) = x_0 quad y(t_0) = y_0 quad y(t_f) = T\nendarray\nright\n\nwhere t_0 in mathbb R, x_0  0, y_0  0 and T  0 are provided.  ","title":"Problem statement"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Main-theorical-results","page":"Introduction","text":"Based on the theoretical developments presented in Dutto et al., 2026, all possible optimal solution structures are characterized by the following result:\n\ntip: Theorem\nUnder standard regularity assumptions, and denoting sigma_- a regeneration arc associated to u = -1,\nsigma_+ a production arc associated to u = +1,\nsigma_s a singular arc associated to u = u_s,the structure of an optimal solution can only be one of the following:sigma_+ \nsigma_-sigma_+  \nsigma_ssigma_+ \nsigma_-sigma_ssigma_+ \ntextor \nsigma_+sigma_ssigma_+\n\nHere, u_s denotes a singular control such that dot x = 0. See Dutto et al., 2026 for a detailed presentation and proof.","title":"Main theorical results"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Reproducibility","page":"Introduction","text":"using Pkg\nusing InteractiveUtils\nusing Markdown\n\n# Download links for the benchmark environment\nfunction _downloads_toml(DIR)\n    link_manifest = joinpath(\"assets\", DIR, \"Manifest.toml\")\n    link_project = joinpath(\"assets\", DIR, \"Project.toml\")\n    return Markdown.parse(\"\"\"\n    You can download the exact environment used to build this documentation:\n    - 📦 [Project.toml]($link_project) - Package dependencies\n    - 📋 [Manifest.toml]($link_manifest) - Complete dependency tree with versions\n    \"\"\")\nend\n\n_downloads_toml(\".\") # hide\n\n<details style=\"margin-bottom: 0.5em; margin-top: 1em;\"><summary>ℹ️ Version info</summary>\n\nversioninfo() # hide\n\n</details>\n\n<details style=\"margin-bottom: 0.5em;\"><summary>📦 Package status</summary>\n\nPkg.status() # hide\n\n</details>\n\n<details style=\"margin-bottom: 0.5em;\"><summary>📚 Complete manifest</summary>\n\nPkg.status(; mode = PKGMODE_MANIFEST) # hide\n\n</details>","title":"Reproducibility"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Parteners-and-Fundings","page":"Introduction","text":"<div style=\"display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; gap: 20px;\">\n    <img src=\"./assets/Logo-INRAE.jpg\" width=\"200px\">\n    <img src=\"./assets/Logo-WOC.png\" width=\"200px\">\n    <img src=\"./assets/Logo-Defi-Region.jpg\" width=\"200px\">\n</div>","title":"Parteners and Fundings"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Control-Toolbox","page":"Turnpike property","text":"","title":"Control-Toolbox"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Studied-Problem","page":"Turnpike property","text":"We now consider a more complex problem where there are two types of masses attached to the membrane, described by two resistances r_1 and r_2. \n\nSince the code provided in the CTMembraneFiltration.jl package only considers the case of one resistance/mass, this page proposes to show how one can use the control-toolbox ecosystem through the OptimalControl.jl package to obtain the optimal solution of the following problem.\n\nusing Plots\nusing OptimalControl\n\n# Problem parameters\nt0 = 0\nvf = 10\nx0 = [0., 0., 0.1, 0.1]\np = [1., 1., 1., 1., 2., 1.5]\n\n# Model functions\ne(x) = p[1] + x[3] + x[4]\ng(x) = p[2]\nf11(x) = p[3]\nf12(x) = - p[4]*x[3]\nf21(x) = p[5]\nf22(x) = - p[6]*x[4]\n\n# Vector fields\nFf(x) = [e(x); g(x); f11(x); f21(x)]  # filtration\nFb(x) = [e(x); -g(x); f12(x); f22(x)] # backwash\nF0(x) = Ff(x) + Fb(x)\nF1(x) = Ff(x) - Fb(x)","title":"Studied Problem"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Optimal-Control-Problem-Definition","page":"Turnpike property","text":"@def begin\n    tf  > t0, variable\n    t   in [t0, tf], time\n    x   = (e, v, r1, r2) in R^4, state\n    u   in R, control\n    -1  <= u(t) <= 1\n\n    x(t0) == x0\n    v(tf) == vf\n\n    xdot(t) == F0(x(t)) + u(t)*F1(x(t))\n\n    e(tf) -> min\nend\n\nAbstract definition:\n\ntf  > t0, variable\nt   in [t0, tf], time\nx   = ((e, v, r1, r2) in R^4, state)\nu   in R, control\n-1  <= u(t) <= 1\n\nx(t0) == x0\nv(tf) == vf\n\nxdot(t) == F0(x(t)) + u(t) * F1(x(t))\n\ne(tf) -> min\n\nThe (autonomous) optimal control problem is of the form: minimize J(x u tf) = g(x(00) x(tf) tf)\n\nsubject to:\n\nxdot(t) = f(x(t), u(t), tf), t in [0.0, tf] a.e.,\nphi- <= phi(x(0.0), x(tf), tf) <= phi+,\nu- <= u(t) <= u+,\n\nwhere x(t) = (e(t) v(t) r1(t) r2(t)) in R^4, u(t) in R and tf in R.","title":"Optimal Control Problem Definition"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Direct-Method","page":"Turnpike property","text":"A classical optimal control method used to obtain a solution of the problem is the direct method. The main idea is to discretize in time the studied optimal control problem, to formulate the associated large optimization problem and to solve it.\n\nThanks to the OptimalControl.jl package, one can easily obtain and plot the solution of the direct method by using the solve function. Here we use the interior point Ipopt solver to obtain a solution of the discretized problem.\n\nusing NLPModelsIpopt\n\n# Solve by direct method\ndirect_sol = solve(ocp; display = true)\n\n# Visualization\nplt_sol = plot(direct_sol, label = \"direct\")","title":"Direct Method"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Structure-of-the-Solution","page":"Turnpike property","text":"The analysis of the solution obtained by the direct method reveals a typical arc structure:\n\n# Analyze solution structure\nstructure = analyze_control_structure(direct_sol)\n\n# Identify arcs\narcs = identify_arcs(direct_sol)\nprintln(\"Identified structure: $(arcs)\")\n\nThe optimal solution typically presents the following structure:\n\nFiltration arc (u = +1): Production with progressive resistance increase\nBackwash arc (u = -1): Regeneration with resistance decrease\nSingular arcs: Optimal transitions between modes","title":"Structure of the Solution"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Structure-Visualization","page":"Turnpike property","text":"# Plot control structure\nplot_control_structure(direct_sol)\n\n# Plot states\nplot_state_evolution(direct_sol)","title":"Structure Visualization"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Indirect-Shooting","page":"Turnpike property","text":"The indirect method is based on Pontryagin's maximum principle. It consists of:\n\nWriting the optimality conditions\nSolving the resulting boundary value problem\nUsing shooting methods to converge to the solution","title":"Indirect Shooting"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Optimality-Conditions","page":"Turnpike property","text":"# Compute Hamiltonian\nH(x, p, u) = e(x) + u * g(x) + p' * (F0(x) + u * F1(x))\n\n# Optimal control\nu_opt(x, p) = sign(g(x) + p' * F1(x))\n\n# Hamiltonian system\nfunction hamiltonian_system(x, p)\n    u = u_opt(x, p)\n    xdot = F0(x) + u * F1(x)\n    pdot = -gradient(x -> H(x, p, u), x)[1]\n    return xdot, pdot\nend","title":"Optimality Conditions"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Shooting-Resolution","page":"Turnpike property","text":"# Configure shooting\nshooting_problem = configure_shooting(ocp, hamiltonian_system)\n\n# Solve\nindirect_sol = solve_shooting(shooting_problem)\n\n# Compare with direct solution\nplot_comparison(direct_sol, indirect_sol)","title":"Shooting Resolution"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Turnpike-Property","page":"Turnpike property","text":"The turnpike property describes the behavior of optimal solutions when the time horizon becomes large. In this context, we observe that:\n\nTrajectories spend the majority of time near an equilibrium state\nFast transitions occur at the beginning and end of the horizon\nThe optimal structure converges to a periodic pattern","title":"Turnpike Property"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Turnpike-Analysis","page":"Turnpike property","text":"# Compute equilibrium state\nequilibrium = compute_equilibrium(ocp)\n\n# Analysis for different time horizons\nhorizons = [5.0, 10.0, 20.0, 50.0]\nsolutions = [solve_with_horizon(ocp, T) for T in horizons]\n\n# Visualize turnpike property\nplot_turnpike_behavior(solutions, horizons, equilibrium)","title":"Turnpike Analysis"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Physical-Interpretation","page":"Turnpike property","text":"The turnpike property has a natural interpretation for membrane filtration systems:\n\nEquilibrium state: Optimal permanent operating regime\nTransitions: Optimal startup and shutdown periods\nAsymptotic behavior: Optimal strategy for continuous operations","title":"Physical Interpretation"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Method-Comparison","page":"Turnpike property","text":"","title":"Method Comparison"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Comparison-Criteria","page":"Turnpike property","text":"Criterion Direct Method Indirect Method\nConvergence Robust Sensitive to initial conditions\nPrecision Moderate High\nComputation time Fast Variable\nStructure analysis Difficult Natural","title":"Comparison Criteria"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Numerical-Results","page":"Turnpike property","text":"# Quantitative comparison\ncomparison_results = compare_methods(direct_sol, indirect_sol)\n\nprintln(\"Direct cost: $(direct_sol.cost)\")\nprintln(\"Indirect cost: $(indirect_sol.cost)\")\nprintln(\"Relative error: $(comparison_results.relative_error)\")","title":"Numerical Results"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Practical-Recommendations","page":"Turnpike property","text":"","title":"Practical Recommendations"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#When-to-use-the-direct-method?","page":"Turnpike property","text":"Problems with complex constraints\nNeed for numerical robustness\nFirst exploration of the problem","title":"When to use the direct method?"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#When-to-use-the-indirect-method?","page":"Turnpike property","text":"Deep theoretical analysis\nNeed for high precision\nSensitivity studies","title":"When to use the indirect method?"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Hybrid-Approach","page":"Turnpike property","text":"An effective strategy consists of:\n\nUsing the direct method for a first estimate\nRefining with the indirect method\nValidating results by sensitivity analysis\n\n# Hybrid approach\nhybrid_sol = hybrid_solve(ocp)\nplot_hybrid_solution(hybrid_sol)","title":"Hybrid Approach"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Extensions-and-Perspectives","page":"Turnpike property","text":"","title":"Extensions and Perspectives"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Possible-Extensions","page":"Turnpike property","text":"More complex models: Inclusion of additional nonlinearities\nState constraints: Limits on resistances\nMulti-objective optimization: Energy cost vs water quality\nStochastic control: Parameter uncertainties","title":"Possible Extensions"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#Research-Perspectives","page":"Turnpike property","text":"Development of adaptive algorithms\nStability analysis of optimal solutions\nExtension to multi-membrane systems\nIntegration with experimental data","title":"Research Perspectives"},{"category":"section","location":"turnpike_property.html#References","page":"Turnpike property","text":"Martinon, P., & Gergaud, J. (2007). Using shooting methods for solving optimal control problems with discontinuities.\nBonnans, J. F., et al. (2017). Optimal control with engineering applications.\nControl-toolbox ecosystem: https://control-toolbox.org/","title":"References"}]
